        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\text{Linear} \\rightarrow y_1 ~ mx_1 + b",
            "\\text{Quadratic} \\rightarrow y_1 ~ ax_1^2 + bx_1 + c"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Domain-restriction",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Domain restriction",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "You can limit which part of the graph is shown by adding a restriction to the equation. For example, to only show the graph",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "of ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "y = x^2",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " for ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "x > 0",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ", you can use ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "y = x^2 \\cdot \\{x > 0\\}",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ".",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Basic-Trigonometry",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Basic Trigonometry",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Other than the basics of what sin, cos, tan each mean, the SAT will sometimes test the following identity. Watch out",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "for it whenever you see things like sin(something) - cos(something else).",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "sin(x) = cos(90 - x)"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Translation",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Translation",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "There are two kinds of translation, horizontal and vertical. Assuming a top-right positive coordinate system, a function",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "f(x)",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " could be translated as follows.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "content" : [
            {
              "inlineContent" : [
                {
                  "text" : "PAY CLOSE ATTENTION TO THE SIGNS, ESPECIALLY FOR HORIZONTAL TRANSLATION. You can think of it like a point being",
                  "type" : "text"
                },
                {
                  "text" : " ",
                  "type" : "text"
                },
                {
                  "text" : "a “preview” of a point a certain distance ",
                  "type" : "text"
                },
                {
                  "code" : "-h",
                  "type" : "codeVoice"
                },
                {
                  "text" : " away.",
                  "type" : "text"
                }
              ],
              "type" : "paragraph"
            }
          ],
          "name" : "Warning",
          "style" : "warning",
          "type" : "aside"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "h\\text{ units right} \\rightarrow f(x-h)",
            "h\\text{ units up} \\rightarrow f(x) + h"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Quadratic-Properties",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Quadratic Properties",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The most advanced SAT questions will be about mostly unknown quadratic properties, eg. sum or product of roots, vertex form, etc.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "For reference, the standar form is:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "y = ax^2 + bx + c"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Vertex-Form",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Vertex Form",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "content" : [
            {
              "inlineContent" : [
                {
                  "text" : "MEMORISE THESE. It will be worth your time.",
                  "type" : "text"
                }
              ],
              "type" : "paragraph"
            }
          ],
          "name" : "Important",
          "style" : "important",
          "type" : "aside"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The vertex form is:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "y = a(x-h)^2 + k"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "To convert from standard form to vertex form, you need to complete the square.  See ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "doc:\/\/Notes\/documentation\/Notes\/Quadratic-functions#Different-forms",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " for how to do that. In summary,",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "y = a(x^2 + \\frac{b}{2a}x) + (- a(\\frac{b}{2a})^2 + c)",
            "",
            "\\text{Where}",
            "",
            "h = -\\frac{b}{2a}",
            "k = -a(\\frac{b}{2a})^2 + c"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "To convert from vertex form to standard form (needed when the question gives you a line of symmetry or vertex), you can expand the square and simplify.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "y = ax^2 + 2ahx + (ah^2 + k)",
            "",
            "\\text{Where}",
            "",
            "b = 2ah",
            "c = ah^2 + k"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "SumProduct-of-Roots",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Sum\/Product of Roots",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\text{Sum of roots} = -\\frac{b}{a}",
            "",
            "\\text{Product of roots} = \\frac{c}{a}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "These can be derived from the quadratic formula. Note that the sum of roots is just double the",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "line of symmetry.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\text{Sum of roots} = \\frac{-b + \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} + \\frac{-b - \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}",
            "",
            "= \\frac{-b + \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac} - b - \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}",
            "",
            "= \\frac{-2b}{2a} = -\\frac{b}{a}",
            "",
            "",
            "\\text{Product of roots} = \\frac{-b + \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \\cdot \\frac{-b - \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}",
            "",
            "= \\frac{b^2 - (b^2 - 4ac)}{4a^2}",
            "",
            "= \\frac{4ac}{4a^2} = \\frac{c}{a}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Polynomials",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Polynomials",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "You don’t really need to know much. Just know that for a point",
              "type" : "text"
            }
